[[Category:Television terminology]]

{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} {{Infobox intangible heritage | Image = Dainichi-dō bugaku godai sonmai 01.jpg | Caption = <!--XXX--> | ICH = ''Dainichido Bugaku'' | State Party = Japan | Domains = Performing arts | ID = 275 | Region = APA | Criteria = <!--???--> | Year = 2009 | Session = 4th | List = Representative | Link = http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/dainichido-bugaku-00275 }}
'''''Dainichido Bugaku''''' ({{lang-ja|links=no|大日堂舞楽}}, literally: Important Day Dance) is a yearly set of nine sacred ritual [[Japanese traditional dance|dances]] and [[traditional Japanese music|music]], named for the imperial palace ensemble performances, "''[[bugaku]]''", and from the palace's ensemble's visit to [[Mount Hachimantai|Hachimantai]], [[Kazuno District, Akita|Kazuno District]], [[Akita Prefecture]], during the reconstruction of the local shrine pavilion, "''Dainichido''", in the early eighth century,<ref name="UNESCO">"[http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/dainichido-bugaku-00275 Dainichido Bugaku]", ''UNESCO.org''.</ref> and their teaching of dances to the locals.
Instruments include the [[flute]] and [[taiko]]. The order and number of dances has changed over time, with the current order of seven dances being the Gongen-mai, Koma-mai, Uhen-mai, Tori-mai, Godaison-mai, Kōshō-mai, and Dengaku-mai dances. Masks include representations of shishi and [[Vairocana]].
The dances have a 1300-year history ([[Nara period]]),<ref>"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/events/2014/12/30/things-to-do/traditional-festivals-things-to-do/dainichido-bugaku-dance-akita/#.V4hxGDXL_uM Dainichido Bugaku Dance in Akita]", ''JapanTimes.co.jp''.</ref> and though interrupted for nearly sixty years in the late eighteenth century, the dances, some of which may include children or masks, are still practiced on January second from sunrise to noon in shrines throughout communities in Osato, Azukisawa, Nagamine, and Taniuchi,<!--all in Kazuno District, Akita--> including Hachimantai.<ref name="UNESCO"/>
Yamaji Kōzō<!--(1984)--> dates ''Dainichido Bugaku'' as arising during and after the [[Nara period|Nara]] (CE 710 to 794) and mid-[[Heian period]]s (CE 794 to 1185), after state support of Shinto temple complexes (originally ordered by [[Emperor Shōmu]] (CE 701 – 756)) began to decline and court and temple performers took residence in local communities, which then preserved genres such as ''Dainichido Bugaku'' as folk arts.<ref>Thornbury, Barbara E. (1997). "Overview", ''The Folk Performing Arts: Traditional Culture in Contemporary Japan'', p.37. SUNY. {{ISBN|9780791432563}}. Also [https://books.google.com/books?id=5wW1AAAAIAAJ&q=%22Dainichido+Bugaku%22&dq=%22Dainichido+Bugaku%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimxPvT6_bNAhUL8mMKHXTHC8UQ6AEINTAE].</ref>
