{{good article}}
{{redirects here|Diamond Lil}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}
{{Use American English|date=October 2017}}

'''Diamond Tooth Lil''' was an American cultural figure popular in the early 20th century as an icon of wealth and libertine burlesque. Several individuals called themselves "Diamond Lil" or "Diamond Tooth", creating an amalgamated legacy clouded by myth. These individuals include a [[vaudeville]] entertainer in the [[Yukon]] during the 1890s [[Klondike Gold Rush]], a [[madam (prostitution)|madam]] in the American West during the early 1900s, and the titular character of [[Mae West]]'s ''[[Diamond Lil (play)|Diamond Lil]]'', who embodied these traits and popularized the name in the 1920s.{{r|Ghosts}}

== Overview ==

Multiple women of the [[American West]] have used the name "Diamond Tooth" and "Diamond Lil".{{r|Rocky Mountains}} In the case of the two most prominent, historians have often confused the lives of Honora Ornstein and Evelyn Hildegard, who both went by the name Diamond Lil around the turn of the 20th century, both emigrants from Austria, with similar ages, careers in entertainment, and diamond-inset teeth.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=121}} They did differ, however, in where they lived: Ornstein in the Klondike and Seattle, and Hildegard in California and Nevada.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|pp=121–122}} Lil became known as enigmatic figure, and has been variously attributed as a "[[dance hall]] girl, gambler, prostitute, or madam who smoked cigars and carried a gun"—a legacy clouded with myth.{{r|Rocky Mountains}} By the 1920s, Diamond Tooth Lil was a [[celebrity|household name]].{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=120}}

== Klondike Lil ==

Honora Ornstein was born in [[Austria-Hungary]] in 1882{{r|Rocky Mountains}} to a Jewish family. She also used the name Lilian Orinstein.{{r|WaPo 1936}} She became famous during the [[Klondike Gold Rush]] in the [[Yukon]] before the turn of the century on the [[Pantages]] [[vaudeville]] circuit, where she was a star entertainer for the region's spendthrift "[[wikt:sourdough|sourdough]]" gold seekers.{{r|NYT obit|WaPo 1936}} A nearby gambling house owner said that Lil spent three or four years there.{{r|WaPo 1936}} Her [[stage name]], Diamond Tooth Lil, is based on her several [[diamond]]-inset [[dental fillings]],{{r|NYT obit}}<ref name="several">{{Cite news |title=Diamond Tooth Lil' Dying: Seattle Hunts Relatives of Beauty of Alaska Gold Rush. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1936-07-01 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B04EFDA1330E13BBC4953DFB166838D629EDE |issn=0362-4331 |df=mdy-all |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> including ones in her [[front tooth|front]] and [[eye tooth|canine]] teeth.{{r|WaPo 1975}} She also collected and wore other diamond-studded jewelry, including a [[white gold]] snake bracelet studded with 125 real diamonds that scaled the length of her arm.{{r|Rocky Mountains|WaPo 1975}} Lil was also known to have come from a wealthy family prior to her time in the Klondike.{{r|WaPo 1936}} Around 1908, she had moved to Seattle and was remembered for ostentatiously throwing money during a Klondikers' parade. Shortly before she divorced her last husband around 1928, she lived in an apartment she had purchased in Seattle and inherited $150,000 from her mother, equivalent to ${{format price|{{inflation|US|150,000|1928}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{r|WaPo 1936}}

Lil made newspaper headlines in 1936{{r|Rocky Mountains}}<!--1935 in NYT?--> when she was committed to [[Western State Hospital (Washington)|Western State Hospital]], a [[psychiatric hospital]] in [[Washington (state)|Washington]],{{r|NYT obit}} and reported as [[near-death]].{{r|WaPo 1936}} By this time, she had sold the diamonds from her teeth but was thought to still have considerable wealth—only she was unable to speak and her relatives were not in contact.{{r|WaPo 1936}} Her reputation limited the market for her jewelry collection, which she struggled to sell in the 1950s.{{r|Rocky Mountains}} Lil's lawyer reported that her assets had been exhausted by 1961.{{r|WaPo 1975}} After spending the remainder of her life in state institutions, Lil died in a Yakima, Washington, nursing home on June 18, 1975.{{r|WaPo 1975}} She was buried in a simple grave{{r|NYT obit}} and had no known relatives.{{r|WaPo 1975}} ''[[The New York Times]]'' remembered Lil as a "[[dance hall]] queen" and "[[:wikt:toast of the town|the toast of the North]]".{{r|NYT obit}}

== Sierra Nevada Lil ==
[[File:Diamond_Tooth_Lil_-_Evelyn_Fialla_1943.png|thumb|1943 photo of Evelyn Fialla, the second Diamond Tooth Lil, with an undated photograph of her from her performing days on the right.]]
Evelyn Fialla was also born in Austria-Hungary, in approximately 1877.{{efn|Based on her reported age of 89 at her death in 1967.<ref name="SanBern">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19785355/diamon_tooth_lil_death/|title=Diamond Tooth Lil Dies at 89|date=1967-09-08|work=The San Bernardino County Sun|access-date=2018-05-03|agency=Associated Press|page=9|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>}} Her family emigrated to the United States and settled in [[Youngstown, Ohio]].{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=120}} She met Percy Hildegard when she was fourteen and eloped with him to Chicago, where she became a saloon singer. She divorced him on an unspecified date, and went on to marry several more times over the course of her life. Sources such as [[Ripley's Believe It or Not!|Ripley's Believe It Or Not!]] reported thirteen marriages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19785516/diamond_tooth_lil_ripleys_believe_it/|title=Ripley's Believe It Or Not!|last=|first=|date=1974-03-04|work=The News-Item|access-date=2018-05-03|location=Shamokin, Pennsylvania|page=14|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=121}} Hildegard herself put the number at eight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/image/v2:114CF38DF1A90B10@EANX-NB-14F84BA39883EAE7@2431067-14F6A4E691F721A2@5-14F6A4E691F721A2@?p=AMNEWS&hlterms=Diamond-Tooth%3B%20Lil|title="Diamond-Tooth Lil" Recalls Gay Days of Era When She Was Toast of Dance Halls of the West|last=Hood|first=Ernie|date=December 8, 1943|work=The Idaho Daily Statesman|access-date=|edition=Wednesday Morning|page=6|via=Boise Public Library Infoweb Newsbank}}</ref> 

As a traveling dancer, she worked her way from Ohio across the West to [[San Francisco]], California.{{sfn|MacKell|2009|p=163}} After the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] left the city in ruins, Hildegard moved to [[Goldfield, Nevada]], a [[boomtown]] of the [[California Gold Rush]]. Hildegard was paid handsomely for her exceptionally popular act at the town's Northern Saloon.<!--${{inflation|US|800|1906}}/month--> Though she ultimately spent less than a year in Goldfield, she quickly opened her own dance hall and had a relationship with [[prospecting|prospector]] [[Diamondfield Jack]]. Hildegard was said to have won her title of Diamond Tooth Lil in a successful bet with a Reno dentist, who set a diamond in her front tooth.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=121}}

Lil was said to have entertained and managed multiple profitable brothels across the West, including [[Death Valley, California]], [[Denver, Colorado]], and [[Boise, Idaho]], where her "Star Rooms" in Boise had amenities including steam heating and both hot and cold water.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=122}}{{r|Rocky Mountains}} She had reached Boise by the early 1940s. In 1944, she announced that her famous front tooth diamond would be willed to the Idaho Children's Home orphanage upon her death. By 1966, she had sold her jewelry and was penniless in California. She died at the Claremont Sanitarium of [[Pomona, California|Pomona]] in 1967.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=122}}

== Mae West ==

{{main|Diamond Lil (play)}}

''[[Diamond Lil (play)|Diamond Lil]]'', the successful Broadway play written and acted by [[Mae West]] in 1928, is assumed but not confirmed to be based on the Lils' lives.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=121}} The show was later adapted into the 1933 film ''[[She Done Him Wrong]]''.{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=122}} West said that her inspiration for the name likely came from her father's nickname for her mother, "Til", short for "Matilda", and sometimes with her drink of choice, "[[Champagne]] Til".<ref name="Chandler2009">{{cite book|last=Chandler|first=Charlotte|title=She Always Knew How: Mae West, a Personal Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DpbBQC8lIg0C&pg=PA119|year=2009|publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]]|isbn=978-1-4165-7913-7|pp=119–120|ref=harv }}</ref> West based the character on herself and viewed Lil as an [[alter ego]].{{sfn|Chandler|2009|p=158}} "The [[femme fatale]] of [[the Bowery]]", declared ''[[The New York Times]]'' of West's Lil in the play's 1949 revival, "bowling her leading men over one by one with her classical impersonation of a storybook strumpet", dressed in "some of the gaudiest finery of the century" with a "snaky walk, torso wriggle, stealthy eyes, frozen smile, flat, condescending voice, [and] queenly gestures"—in all, "a triumph of nostalgic vulgarity".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Atkinson |first1=Brooks |title=Mae West Back in Town as 'Diamond Lil' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1949-02-07 |url=https://partners.nytimes.com/books/97/07/27/reviews/west-diamond.html |accessdate=2017-10-15 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> West won a lawsuit in 1966 against a Los Angeles performer for infringement of the name "Diamond Lil".{{sfn|Oberding|2015|p=122}}

