{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}} {{coord|26.178509|N|91.7350864|E|display=title|source:dewiki}} {{Infobox recurring event |name = Guwahati Theatre Festival |native_name = |native_name_lang = |logo = |logo_alt = |logo_caption = |logo_size = |image = |image_size = |alt = |caption = |status = Active |genre = [[Theatre festival]] |date = <!-- {{start date|df=yes|YYYY|mm|dd}} "dates=" also works, but do not use both --> |begins = <!-- {{start date|df=yes|YYYY|mm|dd}} --> |ends = <!-- {{end date|df=yes|YYYY|mm|dd}} --> |frequency = Annual |venue = Pragjyoti ITA Cultural Complex |location = [[Guwahati]], [[Assam]] |coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> |country = [[India]] |years_active = |first = {{start date|df=yes|2016}} |founder_name = Sunit Jain |last = <!-- Date of most recent event; if the event will not be held again, use {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> |prev = 2017 |next = 2018 |participants = |attendance = |capacity = |area = |budget = |activity = |leader_name = |patron = |organised = [[G Plus]] |filing = |people = |member = |sponsor = <!-- | or sponsors = --> |website = {{URL|http://guwahatitheatrefestival.com/}} |current = |footnotes = }} '''Guwahati Theatre Festival''' is an annual [[theatre festival]] held in [[Guwahati]] city of [[Assam]] state, [[India]].<ref name="ABP"/> The festival is organized by [[G Plus]], an [[English-language]] weekly [[tabloid newspaper]] in [[Guwahati]].<ref name="tnt"/> The festival aims to provide a platform to performing groups to showcase their productions before a new audience in the [[Guwahati]] city and [[Northeast India|North East]] region. == History == The festival was started in 2016 by [[G Plus]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Deka|first1=Prantik|title=Shabana Azmi Enthralls Crowds at G Plus Guwahati Theatre Festival|url=http://www.kothasobi.com/theatre/shabana-azmi-enthralls-crowds-g-plus-guwahati-theatre-festival/|publisher=Kothasobi.com|date=25 November 2017}}</ref><ref name="tnt">{{cite news|title=Assam: 1st Guwahati Theatre Festival to start|url=https://thenortheasttoday.com/assam-1st-guwahati-theatre-festival-to-start-from-sept-14/|publisher=[[The Northeast Today]]|date=7 September 2016}}</ref> === 2016 === The inaugural festival began on 23 September 2016, and featured [[Kalki Koechlin]], [[Saurabh Shukla]], [[Neil Bhoopalam]], [[Rajat Kapoor]], [[Vinay Pathak]], [[Jim Sarbh]], [[Sadiya Siddiqui]], [[Shernaz Patel]], [[Dolly Thakore]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Big theatre groups from Mumbai to perform at Guwahati|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/big-theatre-groups-from-mumbai-to-perform-at-guwahati-716796-2016-09-14|publisher=[[India Today]]|date=14 September 2016}}</ref> and [[Achint Kaur]].<ref name="ABP">{{cite news|last1=Rakshit|first1=Rajibika|title=জোকারদের হ্যামলেটে মন-ধাঁধানো সূচনা গুয়াহাটি নাট্যোৎসবের|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/entertainment/hamlet-the-crown-prince-the-inaugural-play-at-guwahati-theatre-festival-1.478507|publisher=[[Anandabazar Patrika]]|date=15 September 2016|language=Bengali}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chaliha|first1=Akankshya|title=Starburst at theatre festival|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1160914/jsp/northeast/story_108037.jsp|newspaper=[[The Telegraph India]]|date=13 September 2016}}</ref> The maiden festival also featured globally acclaimed play ''Hamlet - The Clown Prince'', directed by [[Rajat Kapoor]] and ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]'' written by [[Eve Ensler]].<ref name="sify">{{cite news|title=First edition of Guwahati Theatre Festival brings a smile to people of northeast|url=http://www.sify.com/news/first-edition-of-guwahati-theatre-festival-brings-a-smile-to-people-of-northeast-news-national-qjxjaPhajeffb.html|publisher=[[Sify.com]]|date=23 September 2016}}</ref>
Other plays staged during the festival was ''The Living Room'', ''2 to Tango 3 to Jive'', ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]'', ''The Truth of Womanhood'', and ''One on One''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shukla|first1=Saurav|title=First edition of Guwahati Theatre Festival brings a smile to people of northeast|url=https://www.topnews.in/law/node/204531|publisher=topnews.in|date=2016-09-23}}</ref>
=== 2017 === The second edition of Guwahati Theatre Festival commenced on 1 November 2017<ref>{{cite news|title=Guwahati Theatre Festival to begin from Nov 1|url=http://www.thehillstimes.in/guwahati-theatre-festival-to-begin-from-nov-1/|publisher=[[The Hills Times (Diphu)]]|date=13 October 2017}}</ref><ref name="BSN">{{cite news|title=Guwahati Theatre Festival to begin from November 1|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/guwahati-theatre-festival-to-begin-from-november-1-117101300492_1.html|agency=[[Press Trust Of India]]|publisher=[[Business Standard]]|date=13 October 2017|location=[[Guwahati]]}}</ref>, featured [[Bollywood]] actors [[Rajat Kapoor]], [[Shabana Azmi]], [[Vinay Pathak]], [[Ranvir Shorey]], and [[Arundhati Nag]].<ref name="tg" >{{cite news|last1=Fauz Hasan|first1=Ali|title=Top Bollywood actors for Guwahati theatre festival|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/north-east/top-bollywood-actors-for-guwahati-theatre-festival-179703|newspaper=[[The Telegraph India]]|date=21 October 2017}}</ref> The festival featured plays like [[Quasar Padamsee]]'s ''[[Mother Courage and Her Children]]'', [[Alyque Padamsee]]'s ''Broken Images'', ''The Gentlemen’s Club'' aka ''Tape''<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gentlemen’s Club aka Tape performed at the Guwahati Theatre Festival 2017|url=http://www.northeastindia24.com/the-gentlemens-club-aka-tape-performed-at-the-guwahati-theatre-festival-2017/|publisher=northeastindia24.com|date=3 November 2017}}</ref> by Sheena Khalid, Vikram Phukan, Puja Sarup, Rachel D'souza. The event also presented two plays based on [[William Shakespeare]]'s works, ''[[What's done is done]]'', and ''Piya Behrupia (Twelfth Night)'' by [[Mumbai]] based two theatre production houses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guwahati Theatre Festival 2017 Concludes With Atul Kumar’s Piya Behrupiya|url=http://www.mediainfoline.com/artnculture/guwahati-theatre-festival-2017-concludes-atul-kumars-piya-behrupiya|publisher=mediainfoline.com|date=7 November 2017}}</ref>
The Guwahati Theatre Festival also conducts workshops for school and college students in various areas of theatrics in collaboration with Brahmaputra Foundation and supported by [[North Eastern Council]], [[Ministry for Development of North Eastern Region]].<ref name="morung" >{{cite news|title=Guwahati Theatre Festival 2017 concludes|url=http://morungexpress.com/guwahati-theatre-festival-2017-concludes/|publisher=[[The Morung Express]]|date=6 November 2017}}</ref> == Sponsors == [[Audi]], [[Ballantine's]], [[State Bank of India]] were the main sponsors of The Guwahati Theatre Festival 2016.<ref name="sify"/> The second edition in 2017 was sponsored by [[Apollo Hospitals]], [[Airtel]], [[Indian Oil]], [[Ballantine's]] and [[Hastakshar]].<ref name="BSN"/>
==Life in a Theatre Award== The festival also constitutes the ''Life in a Theatre Award'' that was given out to Kulada Kumar Bhattacharjee<ref>{{cite news|title=Veteran Actor Kulada Bhattacharjee Awarded ‘Life In A Theatre’ Award|url=https://thenewsmill.com/veteran-actor-kulada-bhattacharjee-awarded-life-theatre-award/|publisher=The News Mill|date=21 September 2016}}</ref> in 2016 and posthumously to [[Padma Shri]] awardee [[Arun Sarma]] in 2017<ref name="morung" /><ref name="tg" />. ==See also== {{Portal|Theatre|Art|Assam|India}} * [[Metropolis Asia]] * [[Alcheringa (festival)]] ==References== {{reflist}}
